#compdef evebox
# =============================================================================
# evebox — Jason Ish's "Web Based Event Viewer (GUI) for
#           Suricata EVE Events" — a Rust-based dashboard server
#           + agent for the SURICATA network IDS/IPS (Intrusion
#           Detection / Prevention System).  Suricata generates
#           EVE (Extensible Event Format) JSON logs at high
#           rates from network traffic monitoring; evebox
#           provides:
#             - SERVER MODE: HTTP dashboard for browsing,
#               filtering, escalating, archiving Suricata
#               alerts; supports both PostgreSQL+Elasticsearch
#               backends and embedded SQLite (no external DB)
#             - AGENT MODE: tail Suricata EVE JSON files and
#               ship to the evebox server (or directly to ES)
#             - ONESHOT MODE: import a finite EVE JSON file +
#               start dashboard in browser (good for offline
#               analysis of pre-captured traffic)
#             - CLI subcommands for direct DB inspection
#               (elastic, sqlite), config management, software
#               update
#           Used at scale by security operations centers
#           (SOCs) running Suricata for network security
#           monitoring; competes with Elastic Stack's Kibana
#           SIEM + Splunk Enterprise Security in the open-
#           source-Suricata niche.
#
# Author:  Jason Ish (Codemonkey.net) — long-time Suricata
#          maintainer (Open Information Security Foundation
#          / OISF, the Suricata steering organization).
#          Jason created evebox in 2014 as a Suricata-focused
#          UI; ported the Go-version backend to Rust in
#          2020-2022 for performance + binary distribution.
# Source:  https://github.com/jasonish/evebox
#          https://github.com/jasonish/evebox/blob/main/src/bin/evebox.rs
# CLI:     src/bin/evebox.rs — uses `clap` builder API (already
#          documented in taxonomy) with global flags + many
#          subcommands.  Headline observability library:
#          `tracing` (tokio-rs/tracing) + tracing-subscriber for
#          structured event logging throughout server + agent.
# Library: tracing (tokio-rs/tracing)
#          ("Application-level tracing for Rust" — Eliza Weisman
#           + Tokio team — released 2018 as the structured-
#           event observability framework for ASYNC Rust services.
#           tracing's central abstractions:
#             - SPAN: a period of time during which a unit of
#               work executes — function calls, request
#               handling, database queries.  Spans carry typed
#               structured fields + nest hierarchically.
#             - EVENT: a discrete observation at a moment in
#               time within a span — log message + fields.
#             - SUBSCRIBER: a collector that receives spans +
#               events; like slog's Drain but with broader
#               capabilities (sampling, filtering, batching,
#               OpenTelemetry export).
#             - LAYER: composable subscriber transformations
#               (filter, format, batch, export) that combine
#               via `.with()` chaining.
#           tracing is the SUCCESSOR to slog (R586) for the
#           Rust ecosystem — adopted by tokio + every modern
#           async-Rust service framework.  Predates Go's
#           context.Value/slog by several years; influenced
#           Java's OpenTracing/OpenTelemetry adoption.)
# License: MIT (evebox); MIT (tracing)
# Status:  evebox — 493+ stars on jasonish/evebox; active
#          maintenance by Jason as part of the broader Suricata
#          ecosystem; tracing — 6300+ stars on tokio-rs/tracing
#          (top-100 Rust GitHub project), 350M+ all-time
#          downloads on crates.io, foundational observability
#          library for tokio + axum + tonic + sqlx + AWS
#          SDK Rust + Cloudflare workers-rs + most modern
#          async-Rust services.
#
