#
# WHAT IS tracing AND WHY IS IT THE 55TH RUST CLI LIBRARY?
#
# tracing (https://github.com/tokio-rs/tracing, 6300+ stars) is
# **Eliza Weisman + the Tokio team's "application-level tracing
# for Rust"** — the MODERN STRUCTURED OBSERVABILITY framework
# that replaced slog as the de-facto choice for Rust services.
# tracing was designed from the start to handle ASYNC RUST's
# unique observability challenges: spans that traverse
# `.await` points, context propagation across task spawning,
# integration with OpenTelemetry and distributed tracing.
#
# tracing's distinguishing characteristics:
#
#   1. SPAN-BASED CONTEXT (not just log lines) — tracing's
#      central abstraction is the SPAN, representing a period
#      of time during which a unit of work executes.  Spans
#      carry typed structured fields + nest hierarchically:
#
#          use tracing::{info, instrument, span, Level};
#
#          #[instrument]
#          async fn handle_request(req_id: u64, user: &str) -> Result<()> {
#              info!("processing request");
#              let result = fetch_data(user).await?;
#              info!(?result, "fetched data");
#              save(req_id, result).await?;
#              info!("saved");
#              Ok(())
#          }
#
#          #[instrument(level = "debug")]
#          async fn fetch_data(user: &str) -> Result<Data> {
#              // Inherits parent span context
#              info!("starting db query");
#              // ...
#          }
#
#      Every event inside `handle_request` automatically
#      carries the span context: `req_id`, `user`, the
#      function name, file/line.  Nested `fetch_data` calls
#      add their own span and child events inherit BOTH
#      parent + child context.  Compare:
#         * slog: contextual loggers via sub-loggers
#         * env_logger: no span concept
#         * zap (Go): structured fields per-call
#         * zerolog (Go): chained fields per-call
#         * tracing: SPANS as TIME-BOUNDED CONTEXT BLOCKS
#                     that nest hierarchically + carry typed
#                     fields automatically
#      FIRST documented Rust logger with span-based context
#      blocks (vs per-call field carrying).
#
#   2. ASYNC-AWARE CONTEXT PROPAGATION — When a span is active
#      and an `.await` happens, tracing automatically pauses
#      the span and resumes it when the future is polled
#      again.  This means:
#
#          let span = info_span!("processing", req_id);
#          let _enter = span.enter();
#          info!("step 1");
#          let result = expensive_operation().await; // span paused
#          // ... possibly run on different task ...
#          // ... possibly long delay ...
#          info!("step 2"); // span re-entered, context preserved
#
#      The `_enter` guard is dropped at end-of-scope, exiting
#      the span.  Tokio-aware: tasks spawned within a span
#      inherit the parent span context across thread boundaries.
#      Compare:
#         * slog: NO async-await awareness
#         * env_logger: NO async-await awareness
#         * tracing: TOKIO-INTEGRATED context propagation
#                     across .await points + task spawning
#      FIRST documented Rust logger with async-aware span
#      context propagation.
#
#   3. SUBSCRIBER + LAYER COMPOSITION ARCHITECTURE — tracing
#      separates EVENT EMISSION (tracing macros) from EVENT
#      COLLECTION (Subscribers) via the Subscriber trait.
#      Subscribers can be composed of multiple Layers via
#      `.with()`:
#
#          use tracing_subscriber::{fmt, prelude::*, EnvFilter};
#
#          tracing_subscriber::registry()
#              .with(EnvFilter::from_default_env())     // RUST_LOG-driven filter
#              .with(fmt::layer().pretty())             // Pretty terminal
#              .with(fmt::layer().json().with_writer(json_file))  // JSON to file
#              .with(tracing_opentelemetry::layer())    // OpenTelemetry export
#              .with(tracing_journald::layer())         // systemd journald
#              .init();
#
#      Each Layer is independently composable.  EnvFilter
#      provides RUST_LOG-syntax compatibility (matching
#      env_logger).  fmt::layer() provides terminal output.
#      Compare:
#         * slog: drain chain composition (similar idea)
#         * env_logger: monolithic
#         * tracing: SUBSCRIBER + LAYER trait architecture with
#                     OpenTelemetry/journald/etc native integration
#      FIRST documented Rust logger with subscriber + layer
#      OpenTelemetry-native composition.
#
#   4. ATTRIBUTE-BASED INSTRUMENTATION — The `#[instrument]`
#      proc-macro attribute automatically wraps a function
#      in an INSTRUMENTED SPAN with all parameters captured
#      as fields:
#
#          #[instrument(level = "debug", skip(database))]
#          async fn get_user(database: &Database, user_id: u64) -> Option<User> {
#              // Span automatically:
#              //  - Named "get_user"
#              //  - Captures user_id as field
#              //  - Skips database (don't log connection pool)
#              //  - At debug level
#              database.find(user_id).await
#          }
#
#      Compare:
#         * slog: manual sub-logger creation in each function
#         * tracing: PROC-MACRO ATTRIBUTE for automatic
#                     function-level span + field capture
#      FIRST documented Rust logger with attribute-based
#      function-level instrumentation.
#
#   5. TOKIO-ECOSYSTEM FOUNDATIONAL PROVENANCE — tracing is
#      THE de-facto observability standard for the tokio
#      ecosystem.  Major users:
#         * tokio (Rust async runtime, 30k+ stars)
#         * axum (web framework)
#         * tonic (gRPC framework)
#         * sqlx (async SQL toolkit)
#         * AWS SDK Rust
#         * Cloudflare workers-rs
#         * tokio-console (THIS author's other tool — R566)
#         * tower (middleware framework)
#         * deno (Deno runtime)
#         * Vector observability platform (Cloudflare)
#         * Linkerd service mesh (control plane)
#         * Most modern async-Rust services 2020+
#         * evebox (THIS — Suricata event viewer)
#         * trailbase (R582 mentioned, env_logger for CLI)
#         * sugar (Solana NFT) — already covered
#      Compare every other documented Rust logger — slog has
#      pre-2020 historical reach; env_logger has rust-cli
#      ecosystem; tracing has TOKIO + ASYNC-SERVICES ecosystem
#      foundational status.  FIRST documented Rust logger with
#      tokio-ecosystem foundational provenance.
#
# tracing's relationship to other documented Rust libraries:
#
#   * Like slog (R586) — both provide structured logging
#   * Unlike slog — adds spans + async context propagation +
#                    OpenTelemetry integration; slog has drain
#                    composition but no async/span concepts
#   * Like env_logger (R582) — both can be initialized via
#                               RUST_LOG env var
#   * Unlike env_logger — far richer feature set
#   * Like color-eyre (R566 _tokio-console) — color-eyre
#                                              integrates with
#                                              tracing for
#                                              spantrace support
#   * Closest cross-language analogs:
#         * Go: OpenTelemetry-Go — similar span-based context
#                + structured events
#         * TS-Node: pino (R584) + OpenTelemetry-JS combination
#                     for similar span+log story
#         * Java: SLF4J + OpenTelemetry (the JVM analog)
#         * Python: structlog + OpenTelemetry-Python
#     tracing is the FIRST documented Rust logger with span-
#     based async-aware context propagation + OpenTelemetry-
#     native composition (the modern Rust observability
#     standard, post-2018 era).
#
